  "description": "A basis of a vector space is a collection of vectors that are, in a precise sense, both sufficient and minimal: sufficient to build every vector in the space, and minimal in that none of them is redundant. A basis gives a coordinate system — once you choose a basis, every vector can be described uniquely by a list of numbers (its coordinates with respect to that basis).\nFormally, a set of vectors {v1,v2,…,vn}\\{v_1, v_2, \\ldots, v_n\\} in a vector space VV is a basis if it satisfies two conditions. First, the set spans VV: every vector in VV can be expressed as a linear combination a1v1+a2v2+⋯+anvna_1 v_1 + a_2 v_2 + \\cdots + a_n v_n for some scalars a1,…,ana_1, \\ldots, a_n from the underlying field. Second, the set is linearly independent: the only way to produce the zero vector as a linear combination is with all coefficients zero (a1v1+⋯+anvn=0a_1 v_1 + \\cdots + a_n v_n = \\mathbf{0} implies a1=⋯=an=0a_1 = \\cdots = a_n = 0). These two conditions together guarantee that the representation of each vector as a linear combination is unique — spanning ensures existence, independence ensures uniqueness.\n",
  "name": "Basis",
